    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-03-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-03-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="884"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d884">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.56352/3–553</note>
                <head>No. 884<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by <persName
                            corresp="#p_DUNHAMWB1">William B. Dunham</persName> of the Office of
                        Western European Affairs</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1953-03-05">March 5, 1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <item>Subject: U.S.–Spanish Negotiations</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>Participants:</head>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_LEQUERICAJF1">Lequerica</persName>,
                        Spanish Embassy</item>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DUNNJC1">Dunn</persName>, U.S. Ambassador
                        to Spain</item>
                </list>
                <p>During Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DUNNJC1">Dunn</persName>’s call on
                    Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_LEQUERICAJF1">Lequerica</persName> this
                    afternoon the Spanish Ambassador referred to his recent trip to Spain. He said
                    that he had reported to <persName corresp="#p_FRANCOYBAHAMONDEF1"
                        >Franco</persName> about the change of administration in the US and, in
                    response to his inquiries, had stated the belief that the new administration
                    would reflect even more good will toward Spain. The Spanish Ambassador said he
                    had also discussed the negotiations with <persName
                        corresp="#p_FRANCOYBAHAMONDEF1">Franco</persName> and, in reply to
                    Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DUNNJC1">Dunn</persName>’s questions said he
                    did not know how <persName corresp="#p_FRANCOYBAHAMONDEF1">Franco</persName>
                    regarded the present status or prospects of the negotiations; that <persName
                        corresp="#p_FRANCOYBAHAMONDEF1">Franco</persName> had maintained a complete
                    poker face. Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_LEQUERICAJF1">Lequerica</persName>
                    expressed his feeling that what is needed now in the negotiations is to get rid
                    of such harsh words as priority and to replace them with some nice fancy
                    words.</p>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_LEQUERICAJF1">Lequerica</persName> also
                    emphasized his belief that the negotiations must be completed at the earliest
                    possible date. He said he fully realizes the problems involved in providing
                    additional funds for Spain in the new foreign aid budget which he understands
                    will probably go before the Congress about the first of May. Consequently he
                    feels that the negotiations should be completed by that time in order to justify
                    new funds for aid to Spain next year.</p>
            </div>
